# CSS Transitions üèÉ

CSS transitions allows you to change property values smoothly, over a given duration.

To create a transition effect, you must specify two things:
1.  The CSS property you want to add an effect to.
2.  The duration of the effect.

```css
div {
  width: 100px;
  transition: width 2s;
}

div:hover {
  width: 300px;
}
```

# CSS Transforms 3D üßä

Adds depth to the transformation.

- `rotateX(deg)`
- `rotateY(deg)`
- `perspective(n)`: How far the object is away from the user.

```css
#myDiv {
  transform: rotateY(150deg);
}
```

# CSS Animations üé¨

Animations let an element gradually change from one style to another.

You can change as many CSS properties you want, as many times as you want.

To use CSS animation, you must first specify some keyframes for the animation.

```css
@keyframes example {
  from {background-color: red;}
  to {background-color: yellow;}
}
```

# Binding Animation üîó

Bind the keyframes to an element.

```css
div {
  animation-name: example;
  animation-duration: 4s;
}
```

# Multi-Stage Animation üìà

Using percentages allows precise control.

```css
@keyframes example {
  0%   {background-color: red; left:0px; top:0px;}
  25%  {background-color: yellow; left:200px; top:0px;}
  50%  {background-color: blue; left:200px; top:200px;}
  75%  {background-color: green; left:0px; top:200px;}
  100% {background-color: red; left:0px; top:0px;}
}
```

# Animation Control üïπÔ∏è

- `animation-iteration-count`: `1`, `infinite`, `3`.
- `animation-direction`: `normal`, `reverse`, `alternate` (forward then backward).
- `animation-play-state`: `paused`, `running` (useful with JS or hover).
- `animation-fill-mode`: `forwards` (retain last style), `backwards`.

```css
div {
  animation: example 5s linear 2s infinite alternate;
}
```

